\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
We use two methods for calculating returns for a given time period.
 The arithmetic average return approach uses the sum of the returns in a
 simulation, while the geometric average return approach uses the product
 of one plus each return.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 be the number of simulated months (36), 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i}$
\end_inset

 be the portfolio return for simulated month 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 given a set of weights, and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{h}$
\end_inset

 be the average portfolio return for simulation 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 given the previous weights; we can express the two approaches as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\text{Arithmetic Average Return: }V_{h}=\frac{1}{t}\sum_{i=1}^{t}r_{i}\label{eq:arith-avg-return-formula}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\text{Geometric Average Return: }V_{h}=[\prod_{i=1}^{t}(1+r_{i})]^{\frac{1}{t}}-1\label{eq:geom-avg-return-formula}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The use of arithmetic returns is mathematically and computationally convenient.
 Our initial analyses utilize the arithmetic average returns before extending
 the mean-CVaR framework to consider geometric average returns and rebalancing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Conditional Value at Risk (CVaR) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
In order to calculate the CVaR of a certain portfolio over a set of simulations,
 we sort the average returns of all the simulations from lowest to highest
 and take the average of the lowest 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
beta * Number of Simulation$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 values.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\beta\text{-CVaR}=\frac{{1}}{(\beta\cdot n)}\sum_{i=1}^{\beta\cdot n}R_{i}\label{eq:CVaR calculation}\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$n$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the number of simulations (1,000), 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the i-th lowest simulated return of the portfolio for a given set of
 weights, and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
beta$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the desired CVaR level (expressed as a percentage, e.g.
 5%).
 We will from now on refer to the 5%-CVaR as simply CVaR.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Analytical Mean-Variance Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "markowitz"

\end_inset

 framework analytically calculates the optimal set of portfolio returns
 and variances using the historical average return and historical standard
 deviation of each asset class along with the historical covariance between
 each pair of asset classes.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{a})$
\end_inset

 denote a set of weights for the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 number of asset classes (seven), 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be the fixed portfolio monthly return rate, and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{i}$
\end_inset

 be the average historical monthly return of asset class 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The optimization problem for one level of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as follows:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\min_{w_{1},w_{2},...w_{n}}\text{{\sigma^{2}}}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{a})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sigma^{2}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{a})=\sum_{i=1}^{a}w_{i}^{2}\cdot\sigma_{i}^{2}+2\sum_{i=1}^{a}\sum_{j>i}^{a}w_{i}\cdot w_{j}\cdot\text{Cov(}i,j\text{) }\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\text{Cov(}i,j\text{)}=\sigma_{i}\cdot\sigma_{j}\cdot\rho_{ij}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
subject to
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{a}>0\label{eq:constraint_noshort}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
w_{1}+w_{2}+...+w_{a}=1\label{eq:constraint_sumto1}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\sum_{i=1}^{a}w_{i}\cdot b_{i}=R\end{equation}

\end_inset

Our two linear constraints indicate that the weights must sum to one and
 be nonnegative (since no borrowing is allowed).
 The optimization uses multiple levels of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 between the lowest and highest single asset class return (where the portfolio
 is 100% weighted in that single asset class) to determine the set of portfolios
 along the efficient frontier.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Single Period Simulated Mean-CVaR Optimization with Arithmetic Returns
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Single-Period-Simulated_arith"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The single period optimization of mean-CVaR minimizes CVaR at each given
 level of return.
 The optimization calculates the CVaR as described in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CVaR calculation"

\end_inset

 while satisfying the condition that the average return across all simulations
 is equal to the given level of return we are optimizing on.
 Since this is a single period optimization, arithmetic returns are used.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be the fixed portfolio monthly return rate as defined before and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 be the calculated portfolio monthly return rate averaged across all simulations.
 The optimization problem for one level of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as follows: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\min_{w_{1},w_{2},...w_{n}}\text{{CVaR}}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{a})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
subject to Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:constraint_noshort"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:constraint_sumto1"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{R}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{a})=R\label{eq:constraint_returnlevel}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\tilde{R}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{n})=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{h=1}^{n}V_{h}\label{eq:constrain_averageportreturns}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \[
V_{h}=\frac{1}{t}\sum_{i=1}^{t}r_{i}\tag{\ref{eq:arith-avg-return-formula}\prime}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
Since we want to optimize on a fixed return, our new constraint is that
 our average final portfolio return 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 across all simulations calculated with arithmetic returns must be equivalent
 to the given fixed portfolio return 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Single Period Simulated Mean-CVaR Optimization with Geometric Returns 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:single-period-Simulated_geom"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
We adopt the geometrically calculated return approach in the this optimization.
 The optimization problem for one level of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\min_{w_{1},w_{2},...w_{n}}\text{{CVaR}}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{a})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
subject to Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:constraint_noshort"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:constraint_sumto1"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:constraint_returnlevel"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
where Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:constrain_averageportreturns"

\end_inset

 holds and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \[
V_{h}=[\prod_{i=1}^{t}(1+r_{i})]^{\frac{1}{t}}-1\tag{\ref{eq:geom-avg-return-formula}\prime}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
Since we want to fix return, our new constraint is that our average final
 portfolio return 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{R}$
\end_inset

 across all simulations calculated with geometric returns must be the same
 as the given fixed portfolio return 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Multiple Period Simulated Mean-CVaR Optimization with Rebalancing and Geometric
 Returns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The implementation is the same as in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:single-period-Simulated_geom"

\end_inset

 with one additional feature: every 12 months, we rebalance the portfolio
 to the predetermined set of weights.
 We calculate return of the portfolio for that year and then redistribute
 the portfolio value according to the predetermined set of weights.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{{V}_{s+1}^{'}}$
\end_inset

 be the portfolio vector after rebalancing in year 
\begin_inset Formula $s+1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{{V}_{s+1}^{'}}$
\end_inset

 contains the value of each asset class at the end of year 
\begin_inset Formula $s+1$
\end_inset

.
 We have the following nonlinear programming optimization problem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\min_{w_{1},w_{2},...w_{n}}\text{{CVaR}}(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{a})\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
subject to Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:constraint_noshort"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:constraint_sumto1"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:constraint_returnlevel"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
where Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:constrain_averageportreturns"

\end_inset

 holds and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V_{h}={V_{f}^{1/t}-1}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{f}$
\end_inset

 is the portfolio after the final rebalancing period.
 For each rebalancing period, the return of the portfolio is calculated
 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
V_{s+1}=V_{s}\prod_{j=q}^{p}(1+r_{j})-1\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\vec{{V}_{s+1}^{'}}=V_{s+1}\cdot(w_{1},w_{2},..,w_{n})\label{eq:rebalance_constraint}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
During the rebalancing period 
\begin_inset Formula $s+1$
\end_inset

, between time periods 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, returns are calculated geometrically.
 Then, at then end of the rebalancing time period 
\begin_inset Formula $s+1$
\end_inset

, we redistribute the value of the portfolio according to a predetermined
 vector of weights to obtain a portfolio vector containing the values of
 each asset class.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\paragraph_spacing double
