\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Single Period (buy and hold) Mean-CVaR 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
We first use
\change_deleted 0 1271685842
d
\change_unchanged
 the resulting weights of the analytical, normal mean-variance efficient
 frontiers to find their corresponding portfolio CVaR's given the simulation
 data.
 We use
\change_deleted 0 1271685848
d
\change_unchanged
 this as a comparison to the actual 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

optimal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 set of portfolios in a mean-CVaR framework.
 The resulting efficient frontiers are shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:meancvar_Single-Per-Arith"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The results indicate that there exists a set of portfolios that has a lower
 CVaR (or higher return) than any of the analytical mean-variance portfolios.
 This is intuitively captured by the fact that optimal mean-CVaR frontier
 lies to the upper left.
 The portfolios that
\change_deleted 0 1271691661
 
\change_unchanged
 maximize return and minimize variance in the previous optimization (Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Analytical-Mean-Variance-Efficient"

\end_inset

) have a greater CVaR than portfolios that
\change_deleted 0 1271691661
 
\change_unchanged
 minimize CVaR.
 This suggests the mean-variance optimization does not protect against situation
s of extreme losses and should not be the only consideration in asset allocation
 especially if preventing extreme downside risk is a central concern.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The convergence of the efficient frontiers at the end points is due to the
 fact that only a portfolio that is 100% weighted in a single asset class
 can achieve the lowest possible return and the highest possible return.
 The outperformance of the optimal mean-CVaR efficient frontier in comparison
 to the mean-variance efficient frontier can be seen in the portfolios between
 the two endpoints.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
Unlike the analytical mean-variance framework, the mean-CVaR framework allows
 for the risk value to be negative.
 A CVaR less than zero means that the worst 5% performance is a negative
 loss or a small gain.
 It is difficult to use an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

information ratio
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Sharpe ratio
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 since the intersection of the efficient frontier and the y-axis leads to
 arbitrarily large ratios.
 It is interesting to note that for an expected loss of 0%, the optimal
 mean-CVaR portfolio will return almost 50 basis points more than the mean-varia
nce portfolio.
 
\end_layout

