\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Rebalancing and Geometric Mean-CVaR
\change_inserted 0 1271686229

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Rebalancing-and-Geometric"

\end_inset


\change_unchanged

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
We demonstrate
\change_deleted 0 1271686102
d
\change_unchanged
 the optimal tradeoff between CVaR and return when comparing single period
 geometric optimization and multiple period (annual) rebalancing optimization
 for a three year simulation period.
 The resulting efficient frontiers are shown in Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:meancvar_Single-Per-Geom"

\end_inset

 & 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:meancvar_Multiple-Per-Rebalancing"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The mean-variance efficient frontier weights are not the most optimal allocation
s in both the rebalancing mean-CVaR framework and the geometric mean-CVaR
 framework.
 The results indicate that an optimal mean-CVaR portfolio exists in both
 the geometric and the rebalancing frameworks that significantly outperforms
 the mean-variance portfolios in the respective frameworks.
 Significant improvement in higher returns or in lower CVaRs can be obtained
 over the normal mean-variance efficient frontiers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The achievement of higher returns and lower CVaR for the geometric portfolios
 in comparison to the rebalancing portfolios, especially at higher risk
 and return levels, must be considered in light of the use of a t-copula.
 This can be visualized by overlaying the geometric mean-CVaR efficient
 frontier with the rebalancing mean-CVaR efficient frontier as seen in Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:meancvar_all3"

\end_inset

.
 The geometric and rebalancing portfolios at lower risk and lower CVaR are
 very similar but quickly diverge as the risk and CVaR increase.
 We believe this is because the t-copula is symmetric, so there exists a
 fat upper tail as well as a fat lower tail.
 In this case, geometric may outperform rebalancing by allowing the portfolio
 to become overweight in high risk-high return assets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
The use of a t-copula to generate simulations appears to play a significant
 role in comparing the efficient frontiers of geometric and rebalancing
 in a mean-CVaR framework.
 
\end_layout

