\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing double
Optimal Mean-CVaR Efficient Frontiers in the Mean-Variance Framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
We use the weights from the resulting optimal efficient frontiers from the
 mean-CVaR framework for single period arithmetic
\change_inserted 0 1271686213
 (Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Analytical-Mean-Variance-Efficient"

\end_inset

)
\change_unchanged
, single period geometric, and multiple period rebalancing 
\change_inserted 0 1271686241
(Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Rebalancing-and-Geometric"

\end_inset

) 
\change_unchanged
and graph them in the mean-variance framework.
 We do this 
\change_inserted 0 1271686179
in order 
\change_unchanged
to compare how much the optimal mean-CVaR portfolios sacrifice in variance
 in order to achieve lower downside losses.
 The resulting efficient frontiers are shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:meanvariance_Corresponding"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
Our results indicate that the optimal mean-CVaR portfolios for all three
 analyses have slightly higher variances than the optimal mean-variance
 efficient frontier (< 0.3%).
 Although there is a slightly higher variance in the optimal mean-CVaR portfolio
s in comparison to the optimal mean-variance portfolios, the optimal mean-CVaR
 portfolios have much less downside risk as CVaR (0.3 - 1.0%).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
This suggests that the cost of protecting against downside risk is only
 slightly higher variance in the portfolio's returns.
 This supports our hypothesis that the mean-CVaR framework, both for single
 period and rebalancing, outperforms the mean-variance portfolio and can
 be a powerful tool to better understand downside risk.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Corresponding Mean-Variance Efficient Frontiers
