\begin_layout Section
\paragraph_spacing double
Introduction
\change_inserted 0 1271547291
 and Literature Review
d308 12
a319 24
The tradeoff between risk and return is the fundamental principle of the
 investment process.
 Although choosing individual investment opportunities is important, the
 top-down analysis of the entire investment portfolio is crucial for maintaining
 and updating investment goals.
 The decision of how to allocate capital 
\change_deleted 0 1271547335
to a few select
\change_inserted 0 1271547336
across
\change_unchanged
 asset classes is a 
\change_deleted 0 1271565552
very important
\change_inserted 0 1271565553
critical
\change_unchanged
 investment decision
\change_inserted 0 1271565568
 that serves as the foundation for building an investment strategy.
\change_deleted 0 1271565571
; the asset allocation has been shown to influence almost 80% of  portfolio
 returns
\begin_inset Note Note
d323 6
a328 1
[citation]
d333 7
a339 19
.
 
\change_inserted 0 1271565580
 
\change_unchanged
Traditional mean-variance asset allocation frameworks use a normal distribution
 to model returns and variance as 
\change_inserted 0 1271565604
its
\change_deleted 0 1271565604
a
\change_unchanged
 risk measure.
 While these traditional methods for understanding risk and return have
 come under fire in the recent financial turmoil, research in alternative
 models is a growing and promising field.
 Recent research focuses on other risk measures for capturing downside risk
 and different probability distributions to account for extreme events
\begin_inset Note Note
d343 10
a352 1
[citation]
d357 1
a357 8
.
 We are interested in building upon the recent research in asset allocation
 
\change_deleted 0 1271565640
models
\change_unchanged
 by investigating how portfolio rebalancing can be included.
 
a360 1
\paragraph_spacing double
d362 13
a374 14
\change_deleted 0 1271547318
The central assumption to asset allocation research and implementation is
 that investors can reasonably model future market behavior using historical
 data and past events.
 The historical return data are fit to probability distributions and correlation
s are used to understand how asset classes behave together.
 The normal distribution has been popular because of the simplicity of obtaining
 an analytical solution to the variance minimization and mean return maximizatio
n problems.
 The assumption that future returns will follow the same distribution as
 historical data allows the simulation of future returns.
 Our research aims to utilize other distributions and joint distributions
 that better account for extreme events in novel asset allocation frameworks.
 
d379 5
a384 1
\paragraph_spacing double
d386 2
a387 9
\change_deleted 0 1271547367
The minimization of risk is required in the asset allocation process.
 Variance may not be the best risk measure to account for downside risk
 since it is a measure of upside and downside volatility.
 Recent research has utilized other risk measures instead of variance to
 better account for downside risk.
 The minimization of these new risk measures has been proven theoretically
 and demonstrated using simulations
\begin_inset Note Note
d391 10
a400 1
[citation]
a404 3
.
 
\change_unchanged
d408 4
d414 17
d432 2
a433 6
\change_deleted 0 1271547377
Our research goal is to build off of the recent advances in asset allocation
 research by developing a rebalancing framework.
 We will investigate how using non-normal probability distributions along
 with downside risk measures perform in a rebalancing asset allocation optimizat
ion problem.
d436 1
a436 2
\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing double
d438 4
a441 6
\change_deleted 0 1271547391
In this paper, we will first present the previous literature and the theoretical
 framework for each concept used in current asset allocation research.
 Next, we will describe our methods and implementation of the different
 parts of the asset allocation models.
 We will then end with our results and discussion.
d443 2
a444 1

d451 6
a456 16
 Markowitz assumed asset returns are normally distributed, 
\change_deleted 0 1271547465
allowing for an analytical solution
\change_inserted 0 1271547468
providing a tractable model for
\change_deleted 0 1271547470
 to
\change_unchanged
 the minimization of variance and the maximization of expected return
\change_inserted 0 1271547448
s
\change_unchanged
.
 The 
\change_deleted 0 1271547449
elegant
a466 19

\change_deleted 0 1271547436
The assumptions of normality and variance as a risk measure in asset allocation
 have come under pressure since the groundbreaking work of Markowitz's portfolio
 theory in light of the market crises in the past two decades.
 Research in the past decade has focused on accommodating the occurrence
 of extreme events and more relevant measures of risk besides variance.
 The application of this research utilizes simulation data to understand
 the tradeoff between risk and return with computer optimization techniques.
 Our research aims to further develop the mean-CVaR framework along with
 the t-Copula probability distribution to incorporate portfolio rebalancing
 and to compare these strategies against traditional mean-variance frameworks.
 
\change_unchanged

\end_layout

